  "suggestion": "[neuroscience+Bayesian-inference+Karl-Friston+information-theory+active-inference] IMPLEMENTATION-READY — Active Inference Engine (final concrete spec). Person = { priors: Record<domain, float>, precision: float, volatility: float }. Situation parsed into observed vector. Free energy F = prediction_error * precision + KL(beliefs, priors). Response = argmin_action F. Five domains: self-model, world-model, other-model, threat-model, resource-model. Each benchmark situation maps to domain-specific prediction errors. Implementation: (1) parse situation into 5 domain signals, (2) compute weighted mismatch vs person priors, (3) select response category that minimizes F. Priors set from person descriptor (anxious → high threat prior, secure → low). Precision modulates sensitivity (trauma → high precision on threat). This gives emotion (which domain activated), behavior (minimizing action), root cause (which prior was violated). — Math: F = Σ_d precision_d * (observed_d - prior_d)^2 + β * KL(updated_beliefs || priors); response = argmin_action E[F | action]; [dynamical-systems+topology+biology+physics+Hopfield-networks] Psychological Landscape (Potential Energy Model). The mind as a Waddington epigenetic landscape: mental states are valleys (attractors), situations are perturbations, responses are trajectories rolling toward nearest attractor. Person = set of attractor basins with depths (stability) and positions (content). Healthy = many shallow basins (flexible). Depressed = one very deep basin. Trauma = deep threat basin with wide catchment. Situation = impulse vector on landscape. Response = attractor reached + energy of transition. Explains: why depression is sticky (deep basin), why flow exists (optimal challenge = shallow basin near edge), why CBT works (basin reshaping), why triggers cause outsized responses (wide catchment areas). Math: gradient flow on U(x) = Σ_i depth_i * exp(-||x - center_i||^2 / width_i). Cross-pollination: Zeeman catastrophe theory, Hopfield networks, Waddington biology. — Math: dx/dt = -∇U(x) + stimulus; U(x) = Σ_i -depth_i * exp(-||x-c_i||^2 / 2σ_i²); response = lim_{t→∞} x(t); [control-theory+biology+cybernetics+homeostasis+dynamical-systems] Hierarchical Homeostatic Regulator (PID Stack). Humans are nested homeostatic controllers maintaining setpoints across 6 levels: physiological → safety → belonging → esteem → meaning → transcendence. Each level runs a PID controller: P=current deviation, I=accumulated unmet need (craving, longing), D=rate of change (urgency, panic). Higher-priority levels suppress lower ones when deviation exceeds threshold. Person = setpoint vector + gain profile. Behavior = corrective action targeting highest-priority violated setpoint. This unifies: anxiety (high D on safety), depression (low setpoints + high I on belonging), addiction (I-term hijacking of physiological loop), flow (all levels satisfied → transcendence available), grief (setpoint recalibration after loss). Cross-pollination: control theory, allostasis, cybernetics, Maslow-reframed-as-dynamics. Implementation: compute deviation per level, select highest-priority, emit corrective behavior category. — Math: u_l(t) = Kp*e_l(t) + Ki*∫e_l dt + Kd*(de_l/dt); active_level = argmax_l {priority_l | |e_l| > threshold_l}; response = corrective_action(active_level, u_active)",
